	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />RESET is a signal telling the CPU to start executing code. Its vector points to the entry point to the code. If you know C or C++, this is similar in ways to the main() function.
<br />
<br /><a href="http://nesdevwiki.org/index.php/NMI" class="postlink">NMI</a> is a non-maskable interrupt. Its vector points to a subroutine that the PPU can tell the CPU to call.
<br />
<br />IRQ is an interrupt. Its vector points to a subroutine that the APU or the Game Pak can tell the CPU to call. You appear to remember APU IRQs from MS-DOS; in that environment, APU IRQ told the running app to point the APU at more samples.
<br />
<br />NMI and IRQ subroutines should end with RTI (return from interrupt), not RTS (return from subroutine).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


